 {"id":"franken_networkx-apo","title":"Document generator MAX_N bounds with rationale comments","description":"## What

Add doc comments to the four MAX_N_* constants in fnx-generators explaining WHY
each specific value was chosen and what would break if they were changed.

## Current Constants (fnx-generators/src/lib.rs lines 13-16)

- MAX_N_GENERIC: 100_000 — general graph generation cap
- MAX_N_STAR: 99_999 (MAX_N_GENERIC - 1) — star graph hub has n edges
- MAX_N_COMPLETE: 2_000 — K_n has n*(n-1)/2 edges; K_2000 = ~2M edges
- MAX_N_GNP: 20_000 — G(n,p) is O(n²); n=20000 → ~200M edge candidates

## Why This Matters

These bounds exist to prevent denial-of-service via adversarial graph generation
(Security Doctrine in AGENTS.md). But they're currently undocumented, which means:
1. A contributor might raise them without understanding memory implications
2. They don't explain the relationship between n and memory (quadratic for complete/GNP)
3. The hardened vs strict mode implications aren't captured

## What To Do

Add comments like:
```rust
/// Maximum nodes for generic generators. Chosen to keep memory under ~1GB
/// for adjacency-list representation with average degree ~10.
const MAX_N_GENERIC: usize = 100_000;

/// Star graph cap. K_{1,n} has exactly n edges, so MAX_N_STAR = MAX_N_GENERIC - 1
/// avoids exceeding the generic edge budget when the hub connects to all others.
const MAX_N_STAR: usize = MAX_N_GENERIC - 1;

/// Complete graph cap. K_n has n*(n-1)/2 edges. K_2000 ≈ 2M edges ≈ 48MB for
/// edge storage alone. Beyond this, memory consumption becomes problematic.
const MAX_N_COMPLETE: usize = 2_000;

/// G(n,p) cap. The naive O(n²) algorithm iterates all n*(n-1)/2 possible edges.
/// At n=20000, that's ~200M iterations — acceptable on modern hardware but any
/// higher risks multi-second generation times even in Rust.
const MAX_N_GNP: usize = 20_000;
```

## Files To Change

- crates/fnx-generators/src/lib.rs (lines 13-16)

## Verification

